IOC: hand over the responsibility of managing the lifecycle of objects to a framework (in this case, the Spring IoC Container).
Control is shifted from the developer to the framework.
Ex. You go to a restaurant and order a burger. The kitchen (the container) handles sourcing the ingredients, cooking,
and serving it to you. You just consume it.

DI: DI is the design pattern used to achieve IoC (How it's happening: Dependencies are passed into the object externally).
Dependency Injection is simply the concrete mechanism used to implement IoC.
Ex. If Class A needs Class B to function, Class B is a "dependency" of Class A. Instead of Class A creating Class B itself,
the Spring Container injects (passes) the instance of Class B into Class A.
```
@Component
   public class Car {
       private final Engine engine;

       // Spring automatically "injects" the Engine bean here
       @Autowired
       public Car(Engine engine) {
           this.engine = engine;
       }

       public void start() {
           engine.run();
       }
   }
```
Benefits:
    Loose Coupling : without creating the new object of the class for this using ApplicationContext
    Easier Testing
    DI

Types:
    Constructor: using constructor
    Setter: using method
    field injection: Loose coupling

TomCat
Definition: Tomcat is a free, open-source Web Server built specifically to run Java-based web applications.

The Analogy: It is to Java what Node.js is to JavaScript. It listens for web traffic and runs your backend code.

