ApplicationContext is the brain of your application. It is the container that creates, configures, and manages all the objects (called Beans) in your program.
Instead of you manually creating objects using the new keyword, the ApplicationContext handles them for you. This is the core of Inversion of Control (IoC).

The Lifecycle of the ApplicationContext
When you run SpringApplication.run(), the ApplicationContext is born and does the following:
Scans: It looks through your project for classes marked with @Component, @Service, @Repository, or 
    @RestController.
Creates (Instantiates): It creates instances (objects) of those classes. These managed objects are 
    called Beans.
Injects (Wires): If Class A needs Class B (using @Autowired), the ApplicationContext automatically injects
    Class B into Class A.
Destroys: When you shut down your application, it cleanly destroys all the objects and frees up memory.

Field Injection
@Autowire
    It tells the Spring ApplicationContext: "Hey, this class needs another class to do its job. 
    Please find that object in your container and plug it in here automatically."

Constructor Injection
private final CarService carService;
@Autowired // Optional in newer Spring versions if there is only one constructor
public CarController(CarService carService) {
    this.carService = carService;
}

Setter Injection
private CarService carService;
@Autowired
public void setCarService(CarService carService) {
    this.carService = carService;
}

@Component is a marker annotation. It tells the Spring ApplicationContext: "Hey, this is a special Java class that you need to manage. Please create an instance (a Bean) of this class and keep it in your container."

When we use two class implementing the one class 
ex. Computer has two child Desktop and laptop so now both have @Component
so we it's being confusing using which class for that purpose we use @Primary

@Primary
It is used when you have multiple beans of the same type, and Spring gets confused about which one it should automatically inject (@Autowired). By placing @Primary on one of those classes, you tell Spring: "If you have to choose between multiple options, make this one your default choice."

What if not use the @Primary
so for this we use @Qualifier 

@Qualifier
While @Primary sets a global default choice when multiple beans of the same type exist, 
@Qualifier lets you manually choose exactly which bean you want at the exact spot you are injecting it.

// --- PLACE ON THE COMPONENT CLASS ---
@Component
@Primary  <-- Here
public class SmsNotification implements NotificationService { ... }


// --- PLACE AT THE INJECTION POINT (CONTROLLER) ---
@RestController
public class NotificationController {

    @Autowired
    @Qualifier("emailService")  <-- Here
    private NotificationService notificationService;
}

If you have a class marked as @Primary (the default), but in your Controller you use @Qualifier("somethingElse"), @Qualifier always wins.

Think of @Primary as a soft recommendation, and @Qualifier as a strict demand.

