H2-DataBase
    H2 is like a whiteboard. It lives entirely inside your computer's temporary memory (RAM). 
    When you start your Spring Boot application, the whiteboard is wheeled in, clean and empty. 
    When you stop your application, the whiteboard is completely erased.
    Why H2?
        Zero Installation
        Speed
        Perfect for Learning and Testing
            
    H2 is a lightweight, invisible database that wakes up when your Spring Boot app starts, saves your data 
    in the computer's temporary memory while you test your APIs, and disappears

        #H2 Console COnfiguration
        h2: 
        console: 
            enabled: true
            path: /h2-console

        #DataBase Connection COnfiguration
        datasource: 
            url: jdbc:h2:mem:testdb
            driver-class-name: org.h2.Driver
            username: sahil
            password: password

        #Show SQL quesries in the console
        jpa:
            show-sql: true

    console: Refers specifically to the H2 Console, which is a built-in web-based user interface used to view your tables.  
    datasource: This section tells Spring Boot where the database is and how to log into it.
    url: jdbc:h2:mem:testdb This is the connection string (address) of your database:
        jdbc:h2: means use the Java Database Connectivity driver for H2.
        :mem: means keep the database entirely in memory (RAM). (It lives and dies with the application restart).
        :testdb is simply the name you are giving to this specific database instance.
    driver-class-name: org.h2.Driver This tells Java the exact underlying class file it needs to load to translate 
        Java commands into H2 database language.
    jpa: This stands for Java Persistence API (managed by Hibernate under the hood). 
        This framework automatically writes SQL queries for you so you don't have to.
        It is similar to the logging: true in the nodeJs for the Development 

    Explore
        Controlling the Logs (Logging)
            When you run your app, you see a wall of text in the console. You can change how much information Spring prints.
            logging:
                level:
                    root: info                    # Standard logs for the whole app
                    org.springframework.web: debug # Shows detailed info about incoming web requests
        Production Monitoring (Spring Boot Actuator)
            If you add the spring-boot-starter-actuator dependency to your project, you get built-in endpoints that 
            let you check if your app is running healthy or view performance metrics.
            management:
                endpoints:
                    web:
                    exposure:
                        include: "health,info,metrics" # Exposes http://localhost:8080/actuator/health
        Custom Application Properties
            You can also make up your own properties! This is incredibly useful for storing values you don't want 
            to hardcode into your Java classes (like external API keys, app versions, or feature flags).
            # You can invent your own keys like this:
            my-app:
                file-upload-limit: "10MB"
                external-api-key: "xyz123abc"

    If you do h2 by mvn repo search h2 database 
    then in the dependency make sure you change from test ---> runtime

Repository
    It is an automated database assistant.
    It acts as a bridge between your Java code and the H2 database.
    Method              What it does in H2
    save(entity)        Inserts a new record, or updates an existing one if the primary key exists.
    findAll()           Fetches every row from the database table (SELECT *).
    findById(id)        Searches for a single record using its primary key.
    existsById(id)      Checks if a record exists (returns true / false).
    delete(entity)      Removes a record from the database.

    Built-In Helper Methods 
        These come standard with JpaRepository
        private ProductRepo repo;
        repo.findAll();
        repo.existsById(id)
        repo.count();
        repo.saveAll(listOfProducts)
        repo.findById()
            .orElseThrow(() -> new ResponseStatusException(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND, "Prod not found"));
        repo.save();
        repo.deleteById();
        repo.deleteAll(); // Truncates or deletes all rows
        repo.deleteAllById(listOfIds); // Deletes specific batch

    Derived Query Methods
        Spring auto-generates the SQL based on the method names
        In interface repo 
        // SELECT * FROM product WHERE category = ?
        List<Product> findByCategory(String category);

        // SELECT * FROM product WHERE price <= ?
        List<Product> findByPriceLessThanEqual(Double maxPrice);

        // SELECT * FROM product WHERE name LIKE '%name%'
        List<Product> findByNameContainingIgnoreCase(String keyword);

        // SELECT * FROM product WHERE category = ? AND price > ?
        List<Product> findByCategoryAndPriceGreaterThan(String category, Double price);
    
    Sorting & Pagination
        // Get all products sorted by price ascending
        List<Product> products = repo.findAll(Sort.by(Sort.Direction.ASC, "price"));    
    
        // Page index starts at 0, page size is 10 items
        Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(0, 10, Sort.by("name"));
        Page<Product> productPage = repo.findAll(pageable);

        List<Product> productsOnPage = productPage.getContent();
        int totalPages = productPage.getTotalPages();
    
    Custom Queries with @Query
        // JPQL (Uses Java Entity fields)
        @Query("SELECT p FROM Product p WHERE p.price > :minPrice AND p.inStock = true")
        List<Product> findAvailableProductsAbovePrice(@Param("minPrice") Double minPrice);

        // Native SQL (Direct DB Query)
        @Query(value = "SELECT * FROM product WHERE discount_percentage > 20", nativeQuery = true)
        List<Product> findHighDiscountProducts();

Hibernate
    It is an Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) framework for Java.
    It is the engine under the hood that translates Java code into SQL queries and talks to your database.

JPA (Jakarta Persistence API): The rulebook/specification. 
    It sets the standard annotations like @Entity, @Id, @Table. 
    It defines what ORM should do, but doesn't write the code.

SpringWebDataBase
    Now we include the Dependency
        Spring Web
        Spring Web devTools
        Spring Data JPA
        H2 DataBase
        LomBok
        Validators
    
    Almost Same as the SpringBootWeb
    Now create a new folder Repository and interface of it 
    
    @Repository 
    public interface ProductRepo extends JpaRepository(Product, Integer){
        // We use the Product, Integer why cause we have Primary key in Integer format that's why 
    }

    Service
        Private ProductRepo repo;
        repo.findAll();
        repo.save();
        repo.findById();
        repo.delete();
        repo.deleteById();
